% emw17Jun: On this reading I realized a few things we can improve: (1) we give away the results a little and should do so less -- we should be asking questions or testing stuff vs telling the audience exactly what we did in a way that gives away what we found, and (2) we need to introduce high and low reproduction states better. 
% emw17Jun: 'limit' gives away the results a little ... 
These constraints may affect how climate---and climate change---impacts seed production. Ideal climatic conditions may trigger higher investment in floral buds only for individual trees not already in a high reproductive state. Warm summers would therefore not affect all trees equally---trees in a high reproductive state would be unaffected, while those in a low reproductive state would likely increase their probability of transitioning to a high reproductive state. Once a reproductive state has been established, then spring frost may have an effect, with damage from frosts most likely to reduce potential seed production for those trees in a high reproductive state. These individual-level reproductive dynamics may then scale up to generate population-level synchrony, with masting emerging through a combination of climatic variability and reproductive constraints. %emw7May -- I would copy this previous sentence to a cover letter file (since it's nice and good point to make there)
%emw7May -- maybe just entirely cut the below OR cut the below and add to the end of the last sentence ", and the potential for improved forecasting with climate change.'
% Accounting for these differential effects of climate could help forecast how climate change may alter masting as an emergent phenomenon of individual reproductive cycles.

Here we investigate how climate affects masting when explicitly modeling how climatic cues interact with individual reproductive constraints to generate population-level synchrony. Using seed data collected on individual trees across populations of beech forests of England since 1980, we first test whether individual trees show evidence for alternative reproductive states % emw17Jun: here's the alternative option of where to tell the reader about high/low states. 
that could lead to masting at the population level. We then use these states to examine how synchrony arises from the combination of reproductive constraints, at the individual-level, and climatic cues that operate over larger scales. % emw17Jun: This sentence gives away the finding: could you re-work it? Using these states, we then examine how synchrony arises at at the individual-level and scales up to populations. (Maybe that is it? Since you already introduce the other stuff...)
Finally, we leverage these results to forecast how future warming may affect both individual tree-level seed production and population-level synchrony. 

\section*{Results and discussion}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=1.1\linewidth]{figures/new/model_overview.pdf} 
  \caption{\textbf{Distinct tree reproductive states generates variability at the population level.} 
  \textbf{(A)} The model identifies two distinct reproductive latent states that correspond to two different level of seed production. 
  \textbf{(B)} The differences in transition probabilities between the two latent states reflect endogenous constraints that shape tree-level reproductive cycles. \textbf{(C)} At the tree level (illustrated here for one arbitrary tree), the alternation between these two latent states across time (upper plot) generates low and high seed production years (lower plot).  \textbf{(D)} When added together across all populations, these individual cycles generate variability and synchrony in seed production across years. In \textbf{(C)} and \textbf{(D)}, the blue line represents the median model prediction, while the shaded areas represent the 25-75\% and 5*95\% quantile ranges. The black lines represent the observed seed counts, and the grey lines and areas indicate model predictions for years when observations were missing.} %emw17Jun: I would just say 50 and 90% quantiles. %vvdm26june: to discuss...
  \label{fig:overview}
\end{figure}

Following the paradigm that masting is defined by of `boom and bust' reproduction, our model identified high and low reproductive years as alternative latent states (Fig. \ref{fig:overview}). In high (`boom') reproductive years, individual trees produced \Sexpr{round(kq$meanseeds_inmasting['50%'],0)} seeds on average (90\% uncertainty range: \Sexpr{round(kq$meanseeds_inmasting['5%'],0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$meanseeds_inmasting['95%'],0)}), while in low (`bust') reproductive years they produced \Sexpr{round(kq$meanseeds_innonmasting['50%'],0)} seeds on average (\Sexpr{round(kq$meanseeds_innonmasting['5%'],0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$meanseeds_innonmasting['95%'],0)} seeds per tree). Seed number per tree in low and high reproductive years, however, overlapped (Fig. \ref{fig:overview}A), with the difference between these two states thus occurring mostly in the opposite extremes: years in the high reproduction latent state included very high seed counts, which would almost never be possible in the low reproduction state, while years in the low reproduction state were characterized by extremely low counts, including a high probability of no observed seeds at all (Fig. \ref{fig:overview}A).

Transitioning between reproductive states (high or low) depended on a tree's state in the previous year (Fig. \ref{fig:overview}B).  In a year with average climatic conditions (mean summer temperatures of \Sexpr{round(kq$meansummertemp,1)}\celsius), a tree in a low reproductive state was most likely to transition to a high reproductive state the next year, with a probability of \Sexpr{round(kq$average_transitiontohigh['50%']*100,0)}\% (\Sexpr{round(kq$average_transitiontohigh['5%']*100,0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$average_transitiontohigh['95%']*100,0)}\%), and a \Sexpr{round(kq$prob_ratio['50%'],1)} times lower probability (\Sexpr{round(kq$average_persistenceinlow['50%']*100,0)}\%, \Sexpr{round(kq$average_persistenceinlow['5%']*100,0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$average_persistenceinlow['95%']*100,0)}\%) of staying in a low reproductive state (Fig. \ref{fig:overview}B).
Under the same average climate, a tree in a high reproductive state was almost certain to transition to a low reproductive state, with a probability of \Sexpr{round(kq$average_transitiontolow['50%']*100,0)}\% (\Sexpr{round(kq$average_transitiontolow['5%']*100,0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$average_transitiontolow['95%']*100,0)}\%), and very unlikely to remain in the same state (\Sexpr{round(kq$average_persistenceinhigh['50%']*100,0)}\%, \Sexpr{round(kq$average_persistenceinhigh['5%']*100,0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$average_persistenceinhigh['95%']*100,0)}\%). 
Trees thus commonly shift into the opposite reproductive state each year, but the low reproductive state is much more persistent (Fig. \ref{fig:overview}C-D). 
Conversely, trees rarely stay in the high reproductive state for more than a single year, supporting the idea of non-mast years being more frequent than mast years \citep{Kelly1994}. 
% Across populations, years of high seed production---mast years---were almost always separated by periods of low seed production (Fig. \ref{fig:overview}D).

%emw17Jun: I would drop the negative signs below based on how it is written.
Climate strongly affected reproductive state transition dynamics. Similar to previous studies \citep{Nussbaumer2018, Vacchiano2017, Journe2024}, we found that warm summer temperatures increased the probability that trees in a low reprodutive state transitioned to a high reproductive state (Fig. \ref{fig:climate}A). For example, the transition probability during a warm summer at \Sexpr{kq$warmsummertemp}\celsius ~was \Sexpr{formatC(kq$warmcold_prob_ratio['50%'], format = "f", digits = 1)} times higher than during a \Sexpr{kq$coldsummertemp}\celsius ~summer (\Sexpr{round(kq$warmsummer_prob['50%']*100,0)}\% vs. \Sexpr{round(kq$coldsummer_prob['50%']*100,0)}\% respectively, and ranges of \Sexpr{round(kq$warmsummer_prob['5%']*100,0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$warmsummer_prob['95%']*100,0)}\% vs. \Sexpr{round(kq$coldsummer_prob['5%']*100,0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$coldsummer_prob['95%']*100,0)}\%).
Additionally, our results support the common hypothesis that spring frosts may limit seed production \citep{Augspurger2009}, with seed production for trees in a high reproductive state reduced by \Sexpr{round(kq$frost_decrease['50%'],1)}\%  (\Sexpr{round(kq$frost_decrease['5%'],1)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$frost_decrease['95%'],1)}\%, Fig. \ref{fig:climate}B) given a three-fold increase in a metric of frost risk \citep[growing-degree days until last frost,][]{Vitasse2018}, but no evidence that warm springs affected seed production (Supp. Fig.). 
Given the reproductive constraints that prevent beeches and many other woody plants from repetitive years of high fruit \citep[from the competitive overlap of flower bud formation and fruit development,][]{Monselise1982, Geber1997}, we assumed the transition from a high to a low reproductive state was not affected by climate (we found strong support for this when we relaxed this assumption, Supp. Fig.). 
