% Trees in a high reproductive state may not neccesarily produce abundant seeds, however, if conditions are not favorable for flower and/or fruit development \citep{Nussbaumer2020}. 

Individual tree-level reproductive states (high or low) scaled up to produce population-level seed production that was synchronous, both within and between populations (sites). Within populations, \Sexpr{round(kq$withinstand_synchrony['50%'],0)}\%  (\Sexpr{round(kq$withinstand_synchrony['5%'],0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$withinstand_synchrony['95%'],0)}\%) of trees shared the same reproductive state on average each year, while synchrony across populations was only slightly lower (the proportion of trees in the same state across all populations was \Sexpr{round(kq$acrossstands_synchrony['50%'],0)}\%, \Sexpr{round(kq$acrossstands_synchrony['5%'],0)} -- \Sexpr{round(kq$acrossstands_synchrony['95%'],0)}\%). This high level of synchrony across populations could suggest that synchrony occurs across wide spatial scales, as sometimes suggested \citep{Bogdziewicz2021a, Journe2024}, but given that these populations were not widely separated spatially (Supp. Mat.), these results only provide evidence for synchrony over smaller spatial scales, as often suggested  \citep{Koenig1998, LaMontagne2020}. %emwFeb5: Will the map show whether there is any autocorrelation in synchrony? As that seems the obvious question from this point and could be worth addressing directly in the text here. 
Whether this scale is sufficient for fitness benefits depends on the exact mechanism (e.g., predator satiation or pollination efficiency) and the species-level attributes \citep[e.g. predators foraging ranges or wind dispersal distances, which depend on seed shape, size and the local landscape,][]{Davies2024}. For example, if beech masting in England mainly serves to overwhelm seed predators, such as wood mouse or bank vole \citep{Sachser2025}, then the masting synchrony at the population level that we observe should be sufficient to maintain the regeneration benefits of masting (given that sites are on average \Sexpr{round(kq$meandistance,0)} km apart, and the two closest sites \Sexpr{round(kq$mindistance,0)} km apart). 
%emw7May -- I would add an estimated foraging distance maybe? 

Climatic cues---especially cold summers---appeared critical to synchronizing the reproductive cycle of individual trees to produce the population-level synchrony that often defines masting \citep{Kelly2002}. 
While \Sexpr{round(kq$average_persistenceinlow['50%']*100,0)}\% of trees in a low reproductive state are likely to stay in that state, cold summer temperatures prevent an additional subset from transitioning to a high reproductive state (because cold summer temperatures reduce the probability of transition to a high reproductive state, Fig. \ref{fig:climate}A). %emw17Jun: can you add fig reference here above?
Thus natural reproductive constraints combined with cold summers can leave most trees in a low reproductive state. This synchrony of low reproduction appears to then drive synchrony of high reproduction when a cold summer is followed by a warm summer; in such years most trees responded consistently to the warm temperatures that promote floral induction, and transitioned together into a high reproductive state (Fig. \ref{fig:climate}C), thus generating a mast year at the population scale. This interplay between individual-level constraints and population-level climatic cues provides a physiological mechanism for reproductive synchrony that can persist over multiple years, and offers a simple explanation for previous findings that masting depends on the temperature difference between successive summers (the $\Delta T$ model; \citealp{Kelly2012}). %emwFeb5: Nice ending! %emw7May -- Also, you should ADD (copy over) this to the cover letter file (it's the sentence I also pulled for the abstract)
% I was referring before to `epigenetic summer memory' \citep{Samarth2020} for deltaT... I don't know if we should leave it? %emwFeb5: Huh? I am not sure that I follow you... 


