These results highlight how biological constraints on plant reproduction may limit runaway effects of climate change. 
For masting, floral bud initiation at the individual tree level is promoted by warm summer temperatures, potentially leading to a higher number of flowers and fruits in the following year \citep{Vacchiano2017, Bogdziewicz2024, Journe2024}. In the next summer, however, the development of a larger fruit load inherently imposes a trade-off that limits the tree from initiating a large number of floral buds again \citep{Monselise1982, Wilkie2008}. These individual-level constraints scale up to the population level by preventing the entire population from producing large seed crops every year---and thus also preventing an unlimited amplification of climate effects on masting. Our results highlight that constraints at the individual level are critical for accurate forecasts of population-scale dynamics (CITE?). Further this approach can help identify the spatial scale at which changes occur, including possible shifts in synchrony. %emw7May -- I suspect any book on individual to population dynamics would have the CITE? point .... 

