\section*{Methods} %emw17Jun: No one sentence paragraphs, even in the methods -- merge them onto the previous paragraphs (you have a couple below). 

\subsection*{Tree-level reproduction and climate data}

We used annual seed production data from \Sexpr{kq$ntrees} individual beech trees (\emph{Fagus sylvatica}) across \Sexpr{kq$nsites} populations in England, collected between 1980 and 2024, following the protocol described in previous publications \citep{Packham2008, Bogdziewicz2021,HacketPain2025}. Populations contained between \Sexpr{kq$ntrees_persite[1]} and \Sexpr{kq$ntrees_persite[2]} trees and were monitored for \Sexpr{kq$nyears_persite[1]} to \Sexpr{kq$nyears_persite[2]} years. Within populations, individual time series varied in length (average length = \Sexpr{kq$avg_nyears_pertree} years) and contained some missing observations. %emw7May -- a little more detail on the missing observations? I guess if Hacket Pain is not clear we do not need to be, but then we should be sure to link directly here to the published data. 

We extracted daily climatic data from ERA5-Land \citep{MunozSabater2021}, at a 0.01 degree resolution, for the \Sexpr{kq$nsites} sites. We computed three climatic variables for each year of observation: average maximum temperature in July and August (of the previous year), average spring temperature (April-May), and growing degree days (GDD) until the last frost day as a measure of spring frost risk \citep{Vitasse2018}.

\subsection*{A Hidden Markov model for individual tree reproduction}

We modeled individual tree seed production with a Hidden Markov Model (HMM), in a Bayesian framework using the probabilistic programming language Stan \citep{Carpenter2017}. 

\subsubsection*{Structure of the model}

In this model, each tree $k$ is assigned to a latent reproductive state $z_{k,i}$ each year $i$: a low reproductive state ($z_{k,i}=1$) or a high reproductive state ($z_{k,i}=2$). The latent state $z_{k,i}$ is conditionally dependent only on the state the preceding year (the \emph{Markovian} assumption), such that for $N$ years we have:

\begin{equation}
p(z_{k,1}, \ldots, z_{k,N}) = p(z_{k,1}) \, \prod_{i = 2}^{N} p(z_{k,i} \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1})
\end{equation}

\noindent The transitions between reproductive states are determined by a $2 \times 2$ matrix of probabilities:
\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}
p(z_{k,i} = 1 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 1) & p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 1) \\
p(z_{k,i} = 1 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 2) & p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 2)
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\noindent  which is by definition equivalent to:
\begin{equation}
\label{matrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1-p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 1) & p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 1) \\
1-p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 2) & p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 2)
\end{bmatrix}\\
\end{equation}

\noindent Both the latent reproductive states and the transition probabilities were inferred from the seed data alone, i.e. the model identify the most probable state sequence for each individual tree given its observed seed counts.

%emw7May -- You could start from this and move down to the tree level ... not saying you need to, but something to consider as it may be more natural to biologists who do less math but think of boom and bust years... 
The latent state determines the observational model responsible for the observed seed count $y_{k,i}$. We modeled the seed production in a low reproductive state with a zero-inflated negative binomial distribution, and the one in a high reproductive state with a negative binomial distribution, such as:

\begin{align}
\label{low}
y_{k,i} \mid z_{k,i} = 1 &\sim \begin{cases} 0 & \text{with probability } \theta \\ \text{NegBin}(\lambda_\text{low}, \psi_\text{low}) & \text{with probability } 1 - \theta \end{cases} \\[2pt]
\label{high} %emw17Jun:  I think we do no more with \text{NegBin}(\lambda_\text{low} in this main model, right? If so we should that somewhere. 
y_{k,i} \mid z_{k,i} = 2 &\sim \text{NegBin}(\lambda_\text{high}, \psi_\text{high})
\end{align}

\subsubsection*{Influence of climate on state transition and seed production}

We expected the climatic conditions experienced by a tree to influence both the transition matrix (Equation \ref{matrix}) and the seeds produced in a high reproductive state (Equation \ref{high}).

%emw17Jun: Hmm, what matrix? Do you mean an equation? You should 'equation' then... here and see below (and this is one of the sentence that needs to merge up)
In Equation \ref{matrix}, we assumed that only the transition from a low reproductive state to a high reproductive state was affected by climate (and thus, by construction, the probability of staying in a low reproductive as well):
\begin{equation}
 p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 1) = \text{logit}^{-1} \left( \alpha_{1 \rightarrow 2} + \beta^\text{summer}_{1 \rightarrow 2} \cdot (X^\text{summer}_{k,i\text{-}1}-X^\text{summer}_\text{baseline}) \right)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $X^\text{summer}_{k,i\text{-}1}$ is the average maximum temperature during summer (the preceding year $i\text{-}1$), $\beta^{summer}_{1 \rightarrow 2}$ is the effect of these summer temperature, and $\text{logit}^{-1}(\alpha_{1 \rightarrow 2})$ is the transition probability when $X^\text{summer}_{t,i\text{-}1}=X^\text{summer}_\text{baseline}$. \\
We did not expect $X^\text{summer}_{k,i\text{-}1}$ to affect $p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 2)$ because the temporal overlap between fruit development and floral bud initiation should prevent trees already in a high reproductive state to respond to favorable summer conditions (though we still checked that this effect was negligible, see Supp. Fig.).

%emw17Jun: What is ref high? 
In Equation \ref{high}, we assumed that both spring temperature $X^\text{spring}_{k,i}$ and spring frost risk $X^\text{frost}_{k,i}$ could impact the seed production in a high reproductive state, such that: %emw17Jun: I think you mean such that, 'such as' reads as one possible example. 
\begin{align}
y_{k,i} \mid z_{k,i} = 2 \sim & ~ \text{NegBin}(\lambda^\text{high}_{k,i}, \psi_\text{high}) \\[2pt]
\log \left(\lambda^\text{high}_{k,i}\right) = & \log(\lambda_\text{high}) 
       + \beta_\text{high}^\text{spring} \cdot (X^\text{spring}_{k,i}-X^\text{spring}_\text{baseline})
       + \beta_\text{high}^\text{frost} \cdot (X^\text{frost}_{k,i}-X^\text{frost}_\text{baseline}) &
\end{align}

\subsection*{Masting synchrony and model predictions} %emw17Jun:  I would cite the figures here when you're giving the methods that go with them, it's helpful to readers. 

Individual tree states were aggregated within and across populations to quantify reproductive synchrony, i.e. the proportion of trees sharing the same reproductive state (Fig. \ref{fig:synchrony}). Synchrony within populations was computed for each population as the maximum of the proportion of trees in a high or low reproductive state, then averaged across populations. Synchrony across populations was computed similarly, but the proportions of trees in each state were first averaged across all populations before taking the maximum (to avoid a population with more trees to have a higher contribution). Synchrony within populations can thus be higher than synchrony across populations when trees within a site tend to be in the same state but differ between sites. Since our model includes only two states, the minimum synchrony is 50\% (i.e. at least 50\% of the trees are in the same state).

To forecast the effects of summer warming (Fig. \ref{fig:future}), we simulated seed production (and synchrony) for 50 trees representing an average English population with projected summer warming up to 7°C over one century \citep{Schumacher2024}. To assess the role of biological constraints, we compared predictions from our model---in which reproductive constraints prevent trees to stay indefinitely in a high reproductive state---against a hypothetical model where summer temperatures had a similar effect on both $p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 1)$ (transition from low to high) and $p(z_{k,i} = 2 \mid z_{k,i\text{-}1} = 2)$ (persistence in high). To illustrate the role of cold summers in reproductive synchrony, we also simulated seed production for 50 trees first experiencing a perfect alternation of cold (around 17\celsius) and warm summers (around 22\celsius), followed by a period of warm summers only (Fig. \ref{fig:hinge}).

